page.text: The purpose of this Safety Study is to identify the crash problems, determine possible
countermeasures that may reduce the crash frequency and congestion as it relates to
signal visibility, lack of left-turn lanes, access management, and signal timing along the
section study area. The proposed countermeasures are then placed in reasonable time
The safety study of the SR 94 (State Road) section extends from reference marker 2.53
to reference marker 3.51 (Trumpeter Boulevard to Lisa Lane) with a total length of 0.98
miles and is identified as number 102 of the year 2009 Highway Safety Program (HSP).
The segment is located in the City of North Royalton, Ohio.
SR 94 is a north-south minor arterial, which intersects SR 82 (Royalton Road) on the
south end of the corridor study. SR 82 is an east-west principal arterial. There are
three signalized intersections within the corridor study, which are SR 94 with SR 82,
Royalton Plaza Drive, and Royalwood Road. SR 94 north of the Royalton Plaza Drive
(Giant Eagle Drive/Post Office Drive) is one lane in each direction. The posted speed
limit along SR 94 is 35 mph within the study section area.
The two predominant crash types in the study area are rear-end and angle crashes. The
majority of the rear-end crashes occurred on the northbound and southbound
approaches to Royalwood Road, and on the northbound and southbound approaches to
the Royalton Plaza Drive intersection. The southbound approach to Royalwood Road
had six rear-end crashes while the northbound approach had four rear-end crashes.
The lack of exclusive left-turn lanes on SR 94 could be a contributing factor with these
The SR 94 and Royalton Plaza intersection experienced six southbound angle crashes,
most of which were attributed to running the red light. Drivers traveling southbound on
SR 94 may be distracted by overlooking the signal heads and looking at the overhead
lane use sign instead, which are just beyond the signal heads. This may also be
contributing to some of the rear-end crashes at this intersection as well. There were
also four angle crashes at the BP gas station drive off of SR 94, which were a result of
exiting vehicles making a right-turn or left-turn through queued traffic.
The intersection of SR 94 and SR 82 area was improved in 2005 with exclusive left and
right-turn lanes for the eastbound, southbound, and westbound approaches and
exclusive left-turn lane for the northbound approach. With this improvement, asphalt
repaving was completed on each approach to this intersection. This year, the rest of
SR 94 within the study area will be repaved. It is recommended that thermoplastic or

The proposed countermeasures can be categorized into three improvement phases,
which are the short-term, medium-term, and long-term phases. For detailed
recommendations, see section 7.0 of the report.
The short-term phase improvements include minor signal timing adjustments at the SR
94 and SR 82 intersection and the SR 94 and Royalton Plaza Drive intersection. In
addition to the minor signal timing changes, it is recommended to put these two traffic
signals in coordination with each other. Other short-term recommendations include:
• Complete an intersection turning movement traffic count and capacity analysis
for the AM and PM peak hours at the SR 94 and Royalwood Road intersection.
• Replace all traffic and pedestrian signal heads to LED at the three signalized
intersections (SR 94 with SR 82, Royalton Plaza, and Royalwood Road).
• Add signal backplates with reflective 2-inch yellow strip to each approach at the
intersection of SR 94 and Royalton Plaza Drives. Check the mast arm supports
to make sure they can handle the additional backplates.
• Relocate the overhead lane use sign mast arm on SR 94 for the southbound
approach to the SR 82 intersection approximately 80 feet further south.
• Remove the lane use signs on the westbound signal arm at SR 94 and
Royalwood Road intersection and install a new lane use ground mounted sign
• Install larger “Do Not Enter” signs at the locations of the existing “Do not Enter”
signs and install new sign posts on the eastbound approach of SR 94 and
• Relocate the advanced street name sign on SR 94 150 feet further south for the
northbound approach to Royalwood Road. This advanced street name sign says
it is 500 feet ahead; however, it is only 350 feet away.
• Replace all non-ADA pedestrian pushbuttons at the intersections of SR 94 &
Royalton Plaza Drive and SR 94 & Royalwood Road.
The estimated cost for the short-term improvements would be $47,600. The average
annual benefit for these short-term improvements would be $216,009.

• Install northbound and southbound left-turn lanes on SR 94 at the Royalwood
Road intersection. The length of the left-turn lanes would come from the capacity

SR 94 is a north-south minor arterial, which intersects SR 82 (Royalton Road) on the
south end of the corridor study. SR 82 is an east-west principal arterial. There are
three signalized intersections within the corridor study, which are shown in Table 1
below. SR 94 north of the Royalton Plaza (Giant Eagle Drive/Post Office Drive) is one
lane in each direction. The posted speed limit along SR 94 is 35 mph within the study
section area. See Figures 1 through 5 for the existing condition diagrams.
The signalized intersection of SR 94 & SR 82 is an actuated signal and operates with
protected/permissive left-turn phasing on all approaches to the intersection (vehicles in
left-turn lanes can make a left-turn on the green arrow or during a green ball after
yielding to through traffic). Signal heads at this intersection are 12-inch incandescent
heads. This intersection was upgraded with added left and right-turn lanes and the
traffic signal was upgraded to mast arms with emergency pre-emption in 2005.
The signalized intersection of SR 94 & Royalton Plaza is a mast arm signal with 12-inch
incandescent signal heads and loop detectors on the side streets. Although this signal
is interconnected to the traffic signal at SR 94 and SR 82, it is currently not in
The signalized intersection of SR 94 & Royalwood Road is a mast arm signal with 12-
inch incandescent signal heads and is actuated. There are left-turn lanes on the
eastbound and westbound approaches on Royalwood Road with left-turn signal
phasing; however, there are no exclusive left-turn lanes on SR 94 at this intersection.
The condition of the asphalt concrete pavement and pavement markings along SR 94
between Trumpeter Boulevard and Royalton Plaza are in good condition (was repaved
in 2005); however, the pavement condition and pavement markings north and south of
these streets are fair to poor condition. This section of SR 94 is planned on being
repaved this year. SR 82 within 700 feet of each side of SR 94 was also repaved in
2005. There is street lighting on utility poles along SR 94 throughout the study area and
A total of 72 crashes were examined, which occurred between the years of 2007 and
2009 (3 years) within the project limits of SR 94. This resulted in a section crash rate of
6.1 per million vehicles per mile for the section (2.53-3.51). The project limits extend
from reference marker 2.53 to 3.51 (south of SR 82 to Lisa Lane) with a total length of
0.98 miles. The crash data summary is in Appendix A

The majority of the rear-end crashes occurred on the northbound and southbound
approaches to Royalwood Road, and on the northbound and southbound approaches to
the Giant Eagle Drive/Post Office Drive intersection. The southbound approach to
Royalwood Road had six rear-end crashes while the northbound approach had four
rear-end crashes. The lack of exclusive left-turn lanes on SR 94 could be a contributing
Areas of higher angle crashes are at the BP driveway off of SR 94 just south of SR 82
(Royalton Road) and the intersection of SR 94 and Giant Eagle Drive/Post Office Drive.
The four angle crashes at the BP gas station drive were a result of exiting vehicles
making a right-turn or left-turn through queued traffic in the northbound through/right
lane and being struck by a vehicle in the northbound left-turn lane. An illustration of this
type of crash is shown below.
Example of vehicle making a left-turn out of a driveway through queued traffic
Angle crashes at the SR 94 and Giant Eagle Drive/Post Office Drive intersection were
mostly due to vehicles running red lights on SR 94. Of the nine angle crashes at this
intersection, five were a result of southbound drivers running the red light.
There was one crash with a pedestrian in which a southbound vehicle backed up at the
Giant Eagle Drive/Post Office Drive intersection and hit a person in a motorized wheel
chair in the crosswalk. Other crashes within the study area are sporadic or are not
enough in a concentrated area to warrant any further analysis.
Injury crashes were just over 29 percent of all crashes within the corridor. Seventy-one
percent of the crashes occurred on dry pavement, 26 percent on wet pavement and
only three percent of crashes occurred on snow covered pavement. Approximately 85
percent of the crashes occurred in daylight hours and the top contributing factors for
crashes were following too close (51%), failure to yield (17%), and ran red light (11%).
A four-hour turning movement count (7-9 AM & 4-6 PM) was completed at SR 94 and
SR 82 signalized intersection on January 26, 2011. The traffic count is in Appendix B.
Based on the four hour volume count and the typical 24-hour variation of traffic on
principal and minor arterials (from the ODOT’s hourly percent by roadway type), the
year 2011 ADT along SR 94 is 11,740. Information from NOACA (regional planning
commission) shows that this area is expected to have a 25.6% growth rate in traffic on
The signalized intersection of SR 94 and SR 82 is coordinated with the traffic signals
east and west of study area along SR 82. This traffic signal is interconnected to the
signal north of this intersection at the Royalton Plaza intersection (Giant Eagle
Drive/Post Office Drive); however, these two signals are not in coordination with each
other. The signal at Royalton Plaza intersection is currently running free. During the
AM peak hour, the cycle length operates at a 95-second cycle length and during the PM
peak hours, the cycle length is 100 seconds. Observations of the AM and PM peak
hours show the signal is efficient and no major queues or delays are experienced.
There are pedestrian pushbuttons for each crosswalk at the SR 94 and SR 82
intersection. However, it was noted that the crosswalk on the west side of the
intersection crossing SR 82 has the Walk interval come up for every cycle and the
crosswalk on the east side of the intersection does not have the Walk interval come up
unless the pedestrian pushbutton is activated. In addition, the pedestrian signals are
quite difficult to see due to either the lenses are getting dirty or the incandescent lights
The existing yellow and all-red times are sufficient for this intersection and no changes
are recommended. However, the Flashing Don’t Walk times are recommended to be
lengthened to 22 seconds for the east-west crossings and 23 seconds for the north-
south crossings. This takes into account subtracting the yellow interval from the
pedestrian clearance calculation and the 3.5 feet per second walking pace, which will be
in the OMUTCD’s next edition. The Walk times could be reduced from 10 seconds to 7
seconds so the side-street phase time doesn’t need to be so long to accommodate the
Capacity is the volume of traffic that can pass through a roadway facility in a given
amount of time (vehicles/hour). The concept of Level of Service (LOS) is a qualitative
measure of the operation of the traffic flow. LOS considers such factors as speed,
travel time, freedom to maneuver, traffic interruptions, driver inconvenience, safety and
delay. For different transportation facilities, the LOS is based on different measures of
Signalized intersections are measured for average control delay in seconds per vehicle.
Control delay includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped delay
and final deceleration delay. The delay measurement for vehicles at a signalized
intersection is a combination of driver discomfort, driver frustration and lost travel time.
The LOS rating system as described in the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual gives a
value of A through F to each type of roadway facility representing best to worst traffic
conditions. When designing for roadway improvements, it is desirable to accommodate
design peak hour volumes at a LOS C or D. Table 2 summarizes the levels of service

The intersection of SR 94 and SR 82 was analyzed in the Synchro software for the AM
and PM peak hours. From this capacity analysis, it shows that the intersection operates
at a LOS C during the AM and PM peak hours with acceptable delays. As part of the
capacity analysis, Synchro was programmed to optimized the signal timings (phase split
times) within the existing cycle lengths. From the optimized results, as shown in Table
3, it shows that the intersection timings are currently optimized and no changes are
recommended for the phase green times. Capacity analysis with the year 2030
volumes shows the intersection will operate at a LOS C and D for the AM and PM peak
hours, respectively. If a northbound right-turn lane was added on SR 94, then the
overall intersection delay would improve slightly to just under five seconds of reduced
delay. Because the year 2030 analysis does not show significant delays or LOS E, it is
not recommended to add any turn lanes at this intersection.

page.text: The signalized intersection of SR 94 and Royalton Plaza operates as a two-phase
signal. Since it is only 450 feet away from the SR 82 signalized intersection, it is
recommended to put this signal in coordination with the SR 82 intersection. This would
help with progression in the northbound and southbound direction. In reviewing the
yellow and all-red times, it is recommend to lengthen the yellow times on phases 2 and
6 (SR 94 through phase) from 3.0 seconds to 3.6 seconds. Based on ODOT’s Traffic
Engineering Manual (TEM), the all-red time guidelines for the north-south phase would
be approximately 1.3 seconds and 1.5 seconds for the east-west phase. The existing
1.0 seconds of all-red time is generally adequate for a smaller intersection such as this;
however, since angle crashes seem to be a problem at this intersection, the all-red time
could be lengthened to 1.5 seconds for the north-south and east-west phases. The
Flashing Don’t Walk time for the east-west phase is adequate at seven seconds;
however the north-south phase should be lengthened to 14 seconds. This takes into
account the 3.5 feet per second walking pace. Walk times are currently set at five (5)
seconds. Since there were pedestrians observed at this intersection (on a winter day at
10 degrees Fahrenheit) and also a person in a motorized wheelchair who lives nearby,
it is recommended to lengthen the Walk time to at least seven (7) seconds.
The signalized intersection of SR 94 and Royalwood Road is a 4-phase signal with left-
turn phases on the east and west approaches. Since there are no left-turn lanes on SR
94 at Royalwood Road, there is just a north-south through phase. During the morning
peak hours, traffic flowed with minimal delays at this intersection. Not that much traffic
was observed on Royalwood Road in the morning peak hours. During the afternoon
hours, it was observed that there was heavy school traffic around 3:00 PM. Northbound
and southbound left-turn vehicles were heavier in the PM peak hours. On average,
there were one to two left-turn vehicles on SR 94 per signal cycle. If there is only one
left-turn vehicle on SR 94 (turning onto Royalwood Road), the through vehicle behind
them usually can get around the left-turning vehicle. This scenario could potentially be
a safety concern if there are both northbound and southbound left-turning vehicles
opposing each other. For example, a driver of the northbound left-turning vehicle may
proceed to make a left-turn through the intersection and not notice the opposing
southbound through vehicle going around southbound left-turn vehicle. However, this
doesn’t seem to occur much, since there were only two left-turn crashes at this
intersection within the last three years. If there are two left-turning vehicles in the same
direction, there is not enough room for through vehicles to get by. In this case, the
through movement could back up significantly; however, this situation did not occur
much during the morning and afternoon peak times observed.
As a short-term recommendation, a traffic count and capacity analysis would be helpful
for the AM and PM peak hours at the SR 94 and Royalwood Road intersection. From
observations, it seems that the eastbound and westbound left-turn phases are not
needed, since very few left-turning vehicles were observed on Royalwood Road.
Northbound and southbound left-turn lanes on SR 94 are recommended as a long-term
recommendation; however, the recommended lengths of the left-turn lanes would come
out of the capacity analysis, which would be completed in the short-term phase.

As a long-term phase recommendation, northbound and southbound left-turns should
be added on SR 94 at the Royalwood Road intersection. The addition of left-turn lanes
should reduce the northbound and southbound rear-end crashes and also reduce
delays at this intersection. From the picture below, left-turns at the intersection can
create backups at the intersection when the traffic signal is green. From observations of
the peak travel times, vehicles do get through in one cycle length, so short-term
changes in the traffic signal phasing is not recommended from a delay or capacity
perspective. However, changing the traffic signal phasing to a north/south split phase
may help in reducing some of the rear-end crashes. Since traffic counts were not
completed at this intersection, it is recommended that traffic counts and capacity
analysis be completed in the short-term phase. The capacity analysis will also give the
recommended lengths of the northbound and southbound left-turn lanes on SR 94.
While the study section does not have a significant amount of business driveways, it is
recommended to still investigate access management concepts, especially near the SR
94 and SR 82 intersection. There are several driveways that can be combined if cross
easement access were implemented, especially on the south side of SR 83 west of SR
94. There are also a few driveways that could be removed that are closest to the SR 94
and SR 82 intersection, such as the two (out of four) driveways accessing BP Gas, the
two driveways (out of four) accessing the gas station on the southwest corner and the
two driveways (out of four) accessing the Sunoco gas station. These driveway removal
recommendations are shown in the Recommended Access Improvements Figure on
The far BP Gas driveway off of SR 94 experienced four angle crashes in three years.
While this is not a significant amount of crashes, it does warrant at least an investigation
of options to consider at this driveway. This driveway could be limited to a right-in, right-
out driveway; however, this could also shift the problem to the driveway off of Royalton
Road. There also isn’t a logical solution in creating an access road to possibly move
the access to SR 94 further south. For these reasons, no changes will be pursued at
this driveway; however, it is recommended to investigate the crashes at this driveway in
a few years to make sure the crash problem isn’t increasing.
